<graphml xmlns="http://graphml.graphdrawing.org/xmlns" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://graphml.graphdrawing.org/xmlns http://graphml.graphdrawing.org/xmlns/1.0/graphml.xsd"><key id="d2" for="edge" attr.name="relation" attr.type="string"/>
<key id="d1" for="node" attr.name="structural_pattern" attr.type="string"/>
<key id="d0" for="node" attr.name="description" attr.type="string"/>
<graph edgedefault="directed"><node id="SOCIAL_CHOICE_IMPOSSIBILITY">
  <data key="d0">No voting system satisfies all fairness axioms (Arrow 1951)</data>
  <data key="d1">Which axiom each system sacrifices IS social choice theory.</data>
</node>
<node id="FOUNDATIONAL_IMPOSSIBILITY">
  <data key="d0">No formal system is consistent + complete + decidable (Godel 1931)</data>
  <data key="d1">Each foundational program = damage allocation strategy.</data>
</node>
<node id="IMPOSSIBILITY_PYTHAGOREAN_COMMA">
  <data key="d0">12 perfect fifths (3/2)^12 != 7 octaves 2^7. Fundamental theorem of arithmetic: no power of 2 equals power of 3.</data>
  <data key="d1">Every tuning system allocates the Pythagorean comma differently. The taxonomy of damage strategies IS music theory.</data>
</node>
<node id="IMPOSSIBILITY_CALENDAR">
  <data key="d0">Solar year (365.2422 days) is not an integer multiple of lunar month (29.5306 days). Ratio is irrational.</data>
  <data key="d1">Every calendar allocates the remainder differently. Aboriginal seasonal calendar dissolves the impossibility by making time elastic.</data>
</node>
<node id="IMPOSSIBILITY_ARROW">
  <data key="d0">No rank-order electoral system satisfies Non-Dictatorship + Unrestricted Domain + Pareto + IIA simultaneously.</data>
  <data key="d1">Condorcet cycles create non-transitive group preference from transitive individual preferences.</data>
</node>
<node id="IMPOSSIBILITY_MAP_PROJECTION">
  <data key="d0">Theorema Egregium: no isometric embedding of a sphere onto a plane. Must sacrifice area, angle, or distance.</data>
  <data key="d1">Every map projection allocates geometric distortion differently. Same structure as tuning systems.</data>
</node>
<node id="IMPOSSIBILITY_CAP">
  <data key="d0">A distributed system cannot simultaneously guarantee Consistency, Availability, and Partition tolerance.</data>
  <data key="d1">Every distributed database sacrifices one of C, A, or P. The taxonomy of which property is sacrificed IS distributed systems theory.</data>
</node>
<node id="IMPOSSIBILITY_BODE_SENSITIVITY_WATERBED">
  <data key="d0">In a linear feedback system, the integral of the logarithm of the sensitivity function over all frequencies cannot be negative; decreasing sensitivity to disturbances at one frequency necessitates inc</data>
  <data key="d1">Cauchy's integral theorem dictates that the integral of the log sensitivity around the right half of the complex plane is conserved. The area under the sensitivity curve is a zero-sum structural invar</data>
</node>
<node id="IMPOSSIBILITY_NO_CLONING_THEOREM">
  <data key="d0">It is impossible to create an identical copy of an arbitrary, unknown quantum state.</data>
  <data key="d1">Quantum mechanics requires all operations to be unitary (linear). The cloning transformation $|\psi\rangle \to |\psi\rangle \otimes |\psi\rangle$ is inherently non-linear.</data>
</node>
<node id="IMPOSSIBILITY_FITTS_HICK_SPEED_ACCURACY">
  <data key="d0">In human motor and decision tasks, response speed and movement accuracy cannot be simultaneously maximized; reducing the time taken to hit a target or make a choice fundamentally increases the error r</data>
  <data key="d1">The human nervous system acts as a noisy Shannon communication channel. Transmitting motor-control information requires time proportional to the required precision (target width). Pushing information </data>
</node>
<node id="IMPOSSIBILITY_IMPOSSIBLE_TRINITY_MACROECONOMICS">
  <data key="d0">A national economy cannot simultaneously maintain a fixed foreign exchange rate, free capital movement, and an independent monetary policy.</data>
  <data key="d1">If a central bank sets an interest rate different from the global rate while capital is free to move, arbitrageurs will flood money in or out, forcing the central bank to print or burn reserves to mai</data>
</node>
<node id="IMPOSSIBILITY_QUINTIC_INSOLVABILITY">
  <data key="d0">No general algebraic solution using radicals for polynomials of degree 5+. S_n not solvable for n&gt;=5 (A_5 is simple non-abelian).</data>
  <data key="d1">Abel-Ruffini/Galois. Damage strategies: PARTITION domain (Galois classification), EXTEND operations (Bring radicals), TRUNCATE to approximation (Newton-Raphson), HIERARCHIZE to transcendentals (ellipt</data>
</node>
<node id="IMPOSSIBILITY_GIBBS_PHENOMENON">
  <data key="d0">Fourier series cannot converge to discontinuous function without permanent ~9% overshoot at jumps. L2 converges but L-infinity does not.</data>
  <data key="d1">Gibbs 1899. Damage strategies: CONCENTRATE ringing at discontinuity, DISTRIBUTE via Cesaro averaging, TRUNCATE via Lanczos windowing, HIERARCHIZE via wavelets, PARTITION via Chebyshev nodes.</data>
</node>
<node id="IMPOSSIBILITY_NO_FREE_LUNCH">
  <data key="d0">No single ML algorithm outperforms random guessing across ALL possible problems. Reducing bias increases variance.</data>
  <data key="d1">Wolpert-Macready 1997. Every ML algorithm is a damage allocation strategy for where to concentrate predictive power.</data>
</node>
<node id="IMPOSSIBILITY_MYERSON_SATTERTHWAITE">
  <data key="d0">No bilateral trading mechanism can be simultaneously efficient, budget-balanced, and individually rational under private overlapping valuations.</data>
  <data key="d1">Information asymmetry makes truth-telling require information rents that break budget balance.</data>
</node>
<node id="IMPOSSIBILITY_MUNDELL_FLEMING">
  <data key="d0">Cannot simultaneously maintain fixed exchange rate, free capital flow, and independent monetary policy.</data>
  <data key="d1">Arbitrage under free capital + fixed rates negates monetary policy. Every nation picks which pillar to sacrifice.</data>
</node>
<node id="IMPOSSIBILITY_CRYSTALLOGRAPHIC_RESTRICTION_V2">
  <data key="d0">Discrete periodic lattice cannot have 5,7,8+ fold rotational symmetry. Rotating by 2pi/5 forces lattice points closer than minimum distance.</data>
  <data key="d1">Resolutions: aperiodic quasicrystals (EXPAND via higher-dim projection), approximant crystals (TRUNCATE), amorphous boundaries (CONCENTRATE), hyperbolic tiling (HIERARCHIZE), stochastic Voronoi (RANDO</data>
</node>
<node id="IMPOSSIBILITY_BODE_INTEGRAL_V2">
  <data key="d0">Integral of log sensitivity over all frequencies = constant. Cannot suppress disturbances at all frequencies. Cauchy integral theorem enforces conservation.</data>
  <data key="d1">THE validation case for damage algebra. Damage conservation is a THEOREM here, not a metaphor. 5 of 7 damage operators instantiated in one engineering domain.</data>
</node>
<node id="IMPOSSIBILITY_BELLS_THEOREM">
  <data key="d0">No local hidden variable theory reproduces all quantum predictions. Bell inequality violated experimentally. Universe cannot be both local and classically real.</data>
  <data key="d1">Each interpretation of QM is a damage allocation: which of locality, realism, or single reality do you sacrifice?</data>
</node>
<node id="IMPOSSIBILITY_BORSUK_ULAM">
  <data key="d0">Any continuous map from S^n to R^n must map some antipodal pair to same value. Sphere wraps back on itself, forcing collision.</data>
  <data key="d1">Governs weather stagnation points, magnetic poles, hairy ball theorem. Every resolution trades a different topological property.</data>
</node>
<node id="IMPOSSIBILITY_GOODHARTS_LAW">
  <data key="d0">A metric cannot simultaneously be accurate measurement AND optimization target. Agents exploit proxy, destroying correlation with true goal.</data>
  <data key="d1">Universal limiting theorem of bureaucracies, algorithms, and AI alignment. Every evaluation system is a damage allocation for where gaming concentrates.</data>
</node>
<node id="HEISENBERG_UNCERTAINTY">
  <data key="d0">Cannot simultaneously know position and momentum with arbitrary precision. Delta_x * Delta_p &gt;= hbar/2.</data>
  <data key="d1">Fourier duality between position and momentum wavefunctions.</data>
</node>
<node id="CARNOT_LIMIT">
  <data key="d0">No heat engine can exceed Carnot efficiency eta = 1 - T_cold/T_hot.</data>
  <data key="d1">Second law of thermodynamics. Entropy must increase.</data>
</node>
<node id="NYQUIST_LIMIT">
  <data key="d0">Cannot reconstruct a signal from samples taken at less than twice its highest frequency.</data>
  <data key="d1">Shannon-Nyquist sampling theorem. Aliasing below Nyquist rate.</data>
</node>
<node id="GODEL_INCOMPLETENESS">
  <data key="d0">No consistent formal system containing arithmetic can prove its own consistency or be complete.</data>
  <data key="d1">Self-reference via Godel numbering creates undecidable sentences.</data>
</node>
<node id="SHANNON_CAPACITY">
  <data key="d0">Cannot transmit information faster than channel capacity C = B log2(1 + SNR).</data>
  <data key="d1">Noise fundamentally limits information transmission rate.</data>
</node>
<node id="HALTING_PROBLEM">
  <data key="d0">No algorithm can decide, for all Turing machines and inputs, whether the machine halts</data>
  <data key="d1">COMPOSE(program + input) → COMPLETE(decision procedure) FAILS → BREAK_SYMMETRY(damage allocation in computation limits)</data>
</node>
<node id="HAIRY_BALL_THEOREM">
  <data key="d0">Every continuous tangent vector field on an even-dimensional sphere has at least one zero</data>
  <data key="d1">COMPOSE(vector field) → COMPLETE(non-vanishing) FAILS → BREAK_SYMMETRY(damage allocation in field design)</data>
</node>
<node id="RUNGE_PHENOMENON">
  <data key="d0">Polynomial interpolation of high degree on equispaced points oscillates wildly near interval ends</data>
  <data key="d1">COMPOSE(nodes) → COMPLETE(polynomial fit) FAILS → BREAK_SYMMETRY(damage allocation in node choice)</data>
</node>
<node id="SEN_LIBERAL_PARADOX">
  <data key="d0">No social welfare function can satisfy Pareto efficiency, minimal liberalism (each individual decisive over some pair), and non-dictatorship simultaneously</data>
  <data key="d1">COMPOSE(preferences + rights) → COMPLETE(welfare) FAILS → BREAK_SYMMETRY(damage allocation in rights aggregation)</data>
</node>
<node id="GIBBARD_SATTERTHWAITE">
  <data key="d0">No non-dictatorial voting rule with three or more outcomes is strategy-proof for all preference profiles</data>
  <data key="d1">COMPOSE(preferences) → COMPLETE(strategy-proof aggregation) FAILS → BREAK_SYMMETRY(damage allocation in voting rule)</data>
</node>
<node id="BROUWER_FIXED_POINT">
  <data key="d0">Any continuous self-map of a compact convex set must have a fixed point; it is impossible to continuously retract a disk onto its boundary | SOURCE: L.E.J. Brouwer, 1911. Uber Abbildung von Mannigfalt</data>
  <data key="d1">MAP(continuous) -&gt; COMPLETE(retraction) FAILS -&gt; BREAK_SYMMETRY(boundary) | WHY: The identity map on the boundary has nontrivial degree; extending it to a retraction would collapse homology, contradic</data>
</node>
<node id="KAKUTANI_FIXED_POINT">
  <data key="d0">Any upper semicontinuous set-valued map from a compact convex set to itself with convex values must have a fixed point; no escape is possible under these conditions | SOURCE: Shizuo Kakutani, 1941. A </data>
  <data key="d1">EXTEND(point-to-set) -&gt; MAP(usc) -&gt; COMPLETE(fixed_point) FORCED | WHY: Approximate selections via Michael selection theorem reduce to Brouwer; convexity of values prevents escape through averaging</data>
</node>
<node id="COVERING_SPACE_OBSTRUCTION">
  <data key="d0">A continuous map lifts to a covering space if and only if its induced fundamental group homomorphism lands in the covering subgroup; otherwise lifting is impossible | SOURCE: Lifting criterion theorem</data>
  <data key="d1">MAP(continuous) -&gt; EXTEND(lift) FAILS -&gt; BREAK_SYMMETRY(fundamental_group) | WHY: The long exact sequence of homotopy groups for the fibration forces pi_1 compatibility; loops in the base that are not</data>
</node>
<node id="KNOT_INVARIANT_INCOMPLETENESS">
  <data key="d0">No single computable knot invariant can distinguish all non-equivalent knots; every known invariant has blind spots where distinct knots receive identical values | SOURCE: Multiple results: Jones poly</data>
  <data key="d1">MAP(knot_to_invariant) -&gt; COMPLETE(discrimination) FAILS -&gt; COMPOSE(multiple_invariants) | WHY: Each invariant captures only partial topological information; mutation operations preserve many polynomi</data>
</node>
<node id="WHITNEY_EMBEDDING_OBSTRUCTION">
  <data key="d0">An n-dimensional manifold cannot always be embedded in R^(2n-1); dimension 2n is necessary in general. Characteristic class obstructions prevent lower-dimensional embeddings | SOURCE: Hassler Whitney,</data>
